We generalise methods of Poonen (\cite{poonenUniversalExistential}) and Koenigsmann (\cite{definingZinQ}) to prove the following theorem.
\begin{theorem*}
  Let $n > 0$ be an integer and $K$ a number field. There exists an existential first-order formula $\varphi_{K,n}(a_0, \dotsc, a_{n-1})$ in the language of rings such that $K \models \varphi_{K,n}(a_0, \dotsc, a_{n-1})$ if and only if the polynomial $X^n + a_{n-1}X^{n-1} + \dotsb + a_0$ has no root in $K$.
\end{theorem*}
Our constructuction of the formula $\varphi_{K,n}$ is explicit in principle, although we have not taken care to optimise its quantifier rank.
As immediate corollaries we obtain:
\begin{corollary*}
  For every $K$ and $n$, the set of $n$-th powers in $K^\times$ is both existentially and universally definable.
\end{corollary*}
This was previously proven in \cite{colliotTheleneVanGeelNthPowers}.

\begin{corollary*}
  Let $K$ be a number field and $K^{\ast\ast} \supseteq K^\ast$ with $K^{\ast\ast} \equiv K^\ast \equiv K$. Then $K^\ast$ is relatively algebraically closed in $K^{\ast\ast}$.
\end{corollary*}
In the case of $K={\mathbb{Q}}$, this answers a question of Koenigsmann.

