\begin{lemma}[{\cite[Corollary IV.3.7]{milneClassFieldTheory}}]
	Let $D$ be a central division algebra of degree $n^2$ over $k$, and let $L$ be a
field of degree $n$ over $k$. Then $L$ splits $D$ if and only if $L$ can be embedded into $D$ over $k$ (i.e.\ there is a subfield of $D$ isomorphic to $L$ over $k$).
\end{lemma}
\begin{lemma}[{\cite[Proposition 2.6.3]{centralSimpleAlgebrasAndGalCohom}}]\label{lemmaHowToComputeNrdAndTrd}
	Let $A/k$ be a CSA of degree $n$ and $x \in A$. If $K \subseteq A$ is a degree $n$ field extension of $k$ containing $x$, then ${\operatorname{Nrd}}(x) = N_{K/k}(x)$ and ${\operatorname{Trd}}(x) = \operatorname{tr}_{K/k}(x)$. In particular, if $n$ is prime and $A$ is a division algebra, then ${\operatorname{Nrd}}(x) = x^n$ and ${\operatorname{Trd}}(x) = nx$ if $x \in k$ and otherwise ${\operatorname{Nrd}}(x) = N_{k(x)/k}(x)$ and ${\operatorname{Trd}}(x) = \operatorname{tr}_{k(x)/k}(x)$.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}[Proof of the proposition]
	This is a local-global principle. Note that there is nothing to show if $A$ is isomorphic to the algebra of $l \times l$-matrices over $K$ since the set on both sides is just $K$ in this case, so we need only cover the case that $A$ is a division algebra. The inclusion $\subseteq$ is clear. For the other inclusion, consider an element $a \in K$ of the right-hand side. We want to show that $a \in S(A/K)$, i.e.\ that there exists $x \in A$ with $\operatorname{Nrd}(x) = 1$ and $\operatorname{Trd}(x) = a$. Let $v_1, \dotsc, v_r$ be the ramified places of $A$. (The local condition is trivial at all other places.)  For each $v_i$ there exists an element $x_i$ of $A \otimes K_{v_i}$ of reduced norm $1$ and reduced trace $a$. We can disregard the case where $x_i$ is in the centre $K_{v_i}$ -- the norm condition would force $x_i$ to be a root of unity, and then the trace condition would force $x_i = \frac a l \in K$, in which case we are done globally. Assume therefore that $x_i \not\in K_{v_i}$, so $K_{v_i}(x_i) / K_{v_i}$ is a field extension of degree $l$ which splits $A \otimes K_{v_i}$ and is generated by an element of norm $1$ and trace $a$. Now globally there exists a field extension $K(x) / K$ of degree $l$ generated by an element of norm $1$ and trace $a$ such that $K_{v_i}(x) = K_{v_i}(x_i)$. To see this, note that we can find a monic polynomial $f$ of degree $l$ over $K$ whose coefficients are close in the $v_i$-adic valuation to the coefficients of the minimal polynomial of $x_i$, for all $i$, and whose constant coefficient is $(-1)^l$ (to force norm $1$) and whose $X^{l-1}$-coefficient is $-a$ (to force trace $a$). Then $f$ is necessarily irreducible over all $K_{v_i}$ and therefore over $K$, and furthermore if $x$ is a root of $f$ in an algebraic closure, then $K_{v_i}(x) =  K_{v_i}(x_i)$ by Krasner's Lemma.
Now the field $K(x)$ splits $A$ by the Hasse-Brauer-Noether Theorem since it splits $A$ everywhere locally, thus $K(x)$ embeds into $A$. The image of $x$ under this embedding has reduced norm $1$ and reduced trace $a$.
\end{proof}

