\subsection{First-order definability}

For what is to follow we will require that $S(A/k)$ is existentially first-order definable (in the language of rings) in terms of structure constants of $A$. (Recall that structure constants are constants $(a_{ijk})_{1 \leq i,j,k \leq l^2}$ in $k$ such that there is a basis $(X_i)_{1 \leq i \leq l^2}$ of $A/k$ satisfying $X_i \cdot X_j = \sum_k a_{ijk} X_k$.) For this it suffices to see that ${\operatorname{Trd}}$ and ${\operatorname{Nrd}}$ are quantifier-freely definable. The perhaps easiest way to verify this is to note that ${\operatorname{Trd}}$ and ${\operatorname{Nrd}}$ are invariant under base change, i.e.\ reduced norm and trace of an element $x$ of $A/k$ are the same as those of the element $x \otimes 1$ of $A \otimes k' / k'$ for any field extension $k'/k$. But ${\operatorname{Nrd}}$ and ${\operatorname{Trd}}$ are clearly definable over algebraically closed fields -- there exists a basis $(Y_i)$ with respect to which the structure constants are those of a matrix algebra, and then determinant and trace are definable -- so ${\operatorname{Nrd}}$ and ${\operatorname{Trd}}$ are quantifier-freely definable over algebraically closed fields by quantifier elimination, and this definition must in fact be correct for all fields.

\begin{corollary}\label{corollaryOpCrossDefinable}
  Fix a number field $K$ and a primitive element $c$ of $K/{\mathbb{Q}}$. Consider the language of rings expanded by a constant symbol for $c$. For any prime ideal $\mathfrak p \triangleleft \mathcal{O}_K$, the ring $\mathcal{O}_{\mathfrak p} \subseteq K$ is positively existentially definable in $K$ in this language.
\end{corollary}
\begin{proof}
  Pick two other prime ideals $\mathfrak p', \mathfrak p'' \triangleleft \mathcal{O}_K$. There exist CSAs $A/K$ and $A'/K$ of degree $2$ that are non-split at exactly the places $\{ \mathfrak p, \mathfrak p' \}$ and $\{ \mathfrak p, \mathfrak p'' \}$, respectively. Then $T_K(A/K) + T_K(A'/K) = \mathcal{O}_{\mathfrak p}$, and this is positively existentially definable in $K$ in the expanded language. (We need to expand the language to make the structure constants of $A$ and $A'$ definable.)
\end{proof}

\section{A diophantine criterion for proper extensions of number fields}




































Fix $n > 1$ and a number field $K$. 
\begin{definition}
  Let $L/K$ be an extension of degree $n$ and $l \leq n$ a prime number. A prime ideal $\mathfrak p$ of $K$ is \emph{$l$-good (for L)} if it is unramified in $L$ and for all prime ideals $\mathfrak q$ of $L$ above $\mathfrak p$ the inertia degree $[\mathcal{O}_L/\mathfrak q : \mathcal{O}_K/\mathfrak p]$ is divisible by $l$.
\end{definition}

\begin{lemma}\label{lemmaGoodness}
  For every $L/K$ of degree $n$ there exists $l \leq n$ such that the set of $l$-good prime ideals of $K$ has density at least $\frac 1 {n!}$. If $n$ is prime, then $l = n$ satisfies this condition.
\end{lemma}
\begin{proof}
  Let $L'/K$ be the Galois hull of $L/K$, $G = {\operatorname{Gal}}(L'/K)$, $H = {\operatorname{Gal}}(L'/L) \lneq G$. Then $\lvert G \rvert \leq n!$. Let $g \in G$ of prime power order such that no conjugate of $g$ is in $H$; existence of such $g$ is assured by the theorem of group theory following below. If $\mathfrak q$ is a prime ideal of $L'$ above an unramified ideal $\mathfrak p$ of $K$ such that ${\operatorname{Frob}}(\mathfrak q/\mathfrak p)$ is conjugate to $g$, then the inertia degree $f(\mathfrak q / \mathfrak p)$ is equal to $\operatorname{ord}(g)$, so for $\mathfrak q' = \mathfrak q \cap L$ we have $f(\mathfrak q' / \mathfrak p) \neq 1$ since ${\operatorname{Frob}}(\mathfrak q/\mathfrak p) \not\in H$, and $f(\mathfrak q' / \mathfrak p) | \operatorname{ord}(g)$. The set of such prime ideals $\mathfrak p$ has density at least $\frac 1 {n!}$ by the Chebotarev Density Theorem. In the special case that $n$ is prime, we can simply choose $g$ to be an element of order $n$ -- since $n \nmid \lvert H \rvert$, no conjugate of $g$ is in $H$.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}[Fein-Kantor-Schacher]
  Let $G$ be a finite group acting transitively on a set $\Omega$ with $\lvert\Omega\rvert > 1$. Then there exists an element $g \in G$ of prime power order acting without fixed points on $\Omega$.
\end{theorem}
\begin{remark}
  Interestingly, the paper \cite{feinKantorSchacher}, in which this theorem was first published, used it with a similar purpose as we do -- classifying relative Brauer groups $\operatorname{Br}(L/K)$ of global fields. 
\end{remark}

