\begin{proposition}\label{propositionCriterionForProperNumberField}
  For a number field $L/K$ consider the following statement:
  \begin{quotation}
    There exists a totally positive element $a \in K^\times$ such that $(a) \in I_{\mathfrak m}$, $(a) \not\in H$ and $a \in T_K((M_i, \sigma_i, a) \otimes_K L / L)^\times$ for all $i$.
  \end{quotation}
  Then this statement is false if $l \nmid [L : K]$, and it is true if $L/K$ is an extension of degree $n$ with $l$ satisfying Lemma \ref{lemmaGoodness}.
\end{proposition}
\begin{proof}
  Let us first cover the case $l \nmid [L : K]$, and assume there were $a$ is in the statement. There must be a prime ideal $\mathfrak p \not\in H$ such that $\mathfrak p$ occurs in $(a)$ with multiplicity not divisible by $l$; this is clear at once when we factorise $(a)$ into prime ideals and remember that $I_{\mathfrak m} / H$ has exponent $l$. Then $\mathfrak p$ is unramified in $M$, but does not split completely, hence there is some $M_i$ in which $\mathfrak p$ is inert, since a prime ideal splits completely in every $M_i$ if and only if it splits completely in $M$. Then the CSA $(M_i, \sigma_i, a)$ does not split at $\mathfrak p$, since $M_i K_{\mathfrak p} / K_{\mathfrak p}$ is an unramified extension of degree $l$ and therefore $a$ is not a local norm. Since $l \nmid [L : K]$, there exists a prime ideal $\mathfrak q$ above $\mathfrak p$ such that $l \nmid [L_{\mathfrak q} : K_{\mathfrak p}]$, so $L_{\mathfrak q}$ does not split $(M_i, \sigma_i, a)$ either.
This implies that $a \not\in T_K((M_i, \sigma_i, a) \otimes_K L /L)^\times$ as $a \not\in \mathcal{O}_{\mathfrak q}^\times$.

  Now consider the case of a proper extension $L/K$ of degree $n$ with $l$ satisfying the lemma. There exist two $l$-good prime ideals $\mathfrak p, \mathfrak p'$ which are unramified in $M/K$, are in the same class in $C_K^+$, and and are in different classes in $I_{\mathfrak m} / H$. This is an easy consequence of density considerations: The set of $l$-good primes has density at least $\frac 1 {n!}$, hence these represent more than $h_K^+$ classes in $I_{\mathfrak m}$ by choice of $l^k$, so we are done by the pigeonhole principle. We now have $\mathfrak{p} \cdot \mathfrak{p'}^{-1} \in P_K^+$, so we can pick a totally positive generator $a \in K^\times$ of this ideal. We claim that $a$ is as desired in the statement. Observe that $(M_i, \sigma_i, a) \otimes L$ splits at all real places because we chose $a$ totally positve, so it suffices to show that this algebra splits at all places of $L$ above $\mathfrak p$ and $\mathfrak p'$. But this is true because of the assumption that $\mathfrak p $ and $\mathfrak p'$ were $l$-good. 
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}
  The statement in the proposition depends only on the ideal $(a)$, i.e.\ its truth value does not change if we multiply $a$ by a totally positive unit element of $\mathcal{O}_K$. To see this, observe that $T_K$ is invariant under multiplication by $\mathcal{O}_K^\times$, and the local splitting behaviour of $(M_i, \sigma_i, a)$ at a prime $\mathfrak p \nmid \mathfrak m$ only depends on the valuation $v_{\mathfrak p}(a)$, since the local norm group contains the local unit group for unramified extensions.
\end{remark}

\begin{theorem}\label{theoremExistentialFormulaForProperNumberFields}
  Consider the first-order language of rings with a unary predicate for a distinguished subset. For every number field $K$ and integer $n > 1$ there exists a positive existential sentence $\psi_{K, n}$ in this language such that $(K, K) \models \neg\psi_{K, n}$, but $(L,K) \models \neg\psi_{K,n}$ whenever $L/K$ is an extension of degree $n$.
\end{theorem}
\begin{proof}
  We shall argue that for every prime number $l \leq n$ the statement from the last proposition is expressible as a sentence $\psi_{K, n, l}$. Then $\psi_{K,n} = \wedge_{l \leq n} \psi_{K, n, l}$ is as desired. It remains to argue for the existence of $\psi_{K,n,l}$. Fix a primitive element $c$ for $K/{\mathbb{Q}}$ and temporarily add a constant symbol for $c$ to our language. In this setting, the following are positively existentially definable:
  \begin{itemize}
    \item The totally positive elements of $K$ -- these are just the sums of four squares.
    \item The elements $a \in K^\times$ such that $(a) \in I_{\mathfrak m}$; these are the $a$ with $a \in \mathcal{O}_{\mathfrak p}^\times$ for all $\mathfrak p | \mathfrak m$, and these are definable by Corollary \ref{corollaryOpCrossDefinable}.
    \item The totally positive elements $a \in K^\times$ with $a \equiv 1 \bmod \mathfrak m$. To see this, let $x \in K$ be an element with $v_{\mathfrak p}(x) = n_{\mathfrak p}$ for all $\mathfrak p | \mathfrak m$. Then $a \equiv 1 \bmod \mathfrak m$ if and only if $a - 1 \in x \cdot \bigcap_{\mathfrak p | \mathfrak m} \mathcal{O}_{\mathfrak p}$.
    \item The ideals $(a) \in I_{\mathfrak m} \setminus H$ generated by totally positive elements $a \in K^\times$. To see this, fix a finite set of representatives $(a_i)$ for those classes in $I_{\mathfrak m} / P_{\mathfrak m}$ that contain an ideal generated by a single totally positive element. Then all ideals $(a)$ as desired are obtained by multiplying one of those representatives in $I_{\mathfrak m} / P_{\mathfrak m} \setminus H / P_{\mathfrak m}$ by an element as in the previous bullet point.
  \end{itemize}
  It is now straight-forward to read off $\psi_{K,n,l}$. It remains to remove the constant symbol for $c$ from our language, but this is easy, as we can simply existentially quantify over the roots of the minimal polynomial of $c$ over ${\mathbb{Q}}$.
\end{proof}



